-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">One Connect Limited is not a unique model of outsourcing as this model operates in other local authority areas besides Lancashire.  It does differ from the traditional understanding of outsourcing of a single se</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rvice tender.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I do believe that this model of outsourcing has the potential to fundamentally erode the foundations on which local government and local democracy stand.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For the past 18 months I have consistently and continually raised concerns about the l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ack of accountability, openness and transparency surrounding One Connect Limited’s operations.  To date One Connect Limited has been a triumph of commercial confidentiality over public interest.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">all the demands the Department for Communities and Local</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Government places on local authorities to be open and transparent and the requirement for the publication of expenditure over £500, joint venture companies behave in exactly the opposite manner – seeking to reveal only limited information, if any at all a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">bout their charges and the financial arrangements with local authorities. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Background</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">One Connect Limited is a joint venture between BT and Lancashire County Council with a 60:40 equity split respectively.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">One Connect Limited provides the following </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">services for Lancashire County Council:</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Human Resources</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Payroll</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">IT support services</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Customer Service functions</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There have been efforts to expand the range of services that are provided by One Connect Limited.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This joint venture company was hailed as a me</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ans through which Lancashire County Council could make financial savings.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In Lancashire a two-tier system of local government exists with the county council and 12 district/borough councils, including West Lancashire Borough Council.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is an opportun</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ity for the lower-level local authorities to enter into an agreement with Lancashire County Council for One Connect Limited to provide these services outlined above.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Currently, West Lancashire Borough Council is the only district / borough council to have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> signed-up to using the One Connect Limited services.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Issues and Challenges One Connect Limited poses for local government </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Councillors prevented from executing their fiduciary duty</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">All councillors have a fiduciary duty to ensure that the council on whi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ch they sit, manages public funds in a responsible manner, maximising their value and use for public benefit whilst ensuring that public money is not put at unnecessary risk.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">”</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In order for councillors to fulfil their fiduciary duty they must have access t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o the appropriate information.  In the case of One Connect Limited I would question how a councillor can carry out this function when they have not been provided with a copy of the contractual agreement between Lancashire County Council and BT and the ongo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing financial and performance indictors.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="3" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In the case of West Lancashire Borough Council the councillors were not provided with a copy of the agreement between Lancashire County Council and West Lancashire Borough Council detailing the service level </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">agreement for One Connect Limited to provide specific council services at the time of making the decision to sign the agreement.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="4" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I am aware that councillors requested this information on several occasions and were refused access to the information.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="5" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I bel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ieve that councillors have been prevented from meeting their fiduciary duties under the guise of commercial confidentiality.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Commercial confidentiality </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">vs.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Public interest</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The issue outlined in the previous section (13) is a prime example of how commercia</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">l confidentiality of One Connect Limited has triumphed over the public interest of the taxpayers of West Lancashire.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We must remember that joint ventures such as One Connect Limited are still 40% owned by council taxpayers and are set-up to provide public</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> services.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="3" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is a question as to whether joint ventures such One Connect Limited should be treated as private companies or as pseudo-public sector organisations.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="4" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In these circumstances what is the correct balance between maintaining the commercial co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nfidentiality and ensuring the public interest is protected</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and enabling councillors to meet their fiduciary duty</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">?</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Commercial capacity an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> expertise within local authorities</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">One of the concerns relating to One Connect Limited is the length of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">contract</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to which local authorities are tied-into and the cost to extricate themselves from the contract early.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This concern reflects a fundamental problem in how these contracts and joint ventures are constructed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and how the local authority is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> at a disadvantage.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="3" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Experiences show that in many instances local authorities do not have the senior staff with the requisite commercial skills to negotiate on an equal footing with their corporate and private sector colleagues.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="4" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is one example, not related to One Connect Limited, but still from West Lancashire that I can use to highlight the commercial expertise limitations within local authorities.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">West Lancashire Borough Council enter</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed into a 15-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">year partnership agreemen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t for a town centre redevelopment scheme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with a private developer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  The deal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">they </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sign</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed contained</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> no break clauses giving control of public assets to the private developer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for the duration of the contract</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This has allowed the private developer to sit on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the assets and residents have yet to see any development after seven years of the agreement have lapsed.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This is another example of a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">local authority let </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">contract with the private sector, which shows local government does not have the commercial expertis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e and is not up to contracting with private sector partners. </span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="5" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Therefore, how can the council taxpayer within a local authority be protected from being ripped-off</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> by large corporate organisations in the contract negotiations so as to ensure protection of t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he public interest over commercial gain?</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Ability to determine value for money</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Due to the fundamental lack of information in the public domain it remains impossible for councillors to determine if this contract constitutes value for money.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There have been</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> reports in the media based on anecdotal evidence that the costs local authorities are charged by organisations such as One Connect Limited for items such as IT equipment is significantly higher than the council would be expected to pay if they sourced the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> equipment themselves.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="3" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">If we accept the media reports have some basis then it brings into question if over the course of the contract the local authority is getting value for money.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="4" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">At present the case cannot be made either for or against value for money</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in this deal simply because the relevant costings </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and charges are not available to all councillors in order for them to make such an assessment.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="5" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is a clear strategy to equate initial savings in the contract with value for money.  For example, I </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have been told by West Lancashire Borough Council that One Connect Limited providing services is a good deal because it saves £500,000.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="6" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.11pt; padding-left:6.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, is this saving f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or the lifetime of the contract? W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hat is the standard of service that will be provi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ded in retu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rn for those savings? W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hat is the impact on the local community if there are significan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t reductions in staffing levels? W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hat profit is the private company making and could greater savings be achi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eved in different circumstances?</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="7" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Equating immediate savings </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with value for money is fundamentally flawed and misleading.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="8" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Therefore, within this context how can councillors be reassured that council taxpayers are getting a good deal if they are unable to determine if the contract does constitute value for money.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Inability to assess performance and delivery effectively</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">One Connect Limited has a duty and a responsibility to regularly report its performance </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to the local authorities to which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> it provides services.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Based on the reports submitted by One Connect Limited </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to both Lancashire County Council and West Lancashire Borough Council, which are in the public domain, there is insufficient information contained within the reports for any meaningful scrutiny of performance.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="3" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There has been one occasion in which One Conn</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ect Limited outsourced work to Liverpool Direct Limited.  There was a backlog in the processing of welfare benefits data.  To clear the backlog this task was delegated to another organisation.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="4" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A decision to delegate such work raises a whole series of ques</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tions:</span></li><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 104pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In the first instance data protection for individuals having their details passed between two organisations that are in essence two sep</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">arate companies?</span></li></ol></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 108pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="2" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="2" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 104pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Is there an agreement in place to allow for the delegation of such tasks and if so then why i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">his not in the public domain?</span></li></ol></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="3" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="3" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 104pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">How can councillors scrutinise why this situation and how it can be managed in the future if such incidents are not formally reported to them in perfo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rmance data and council reports?</span></li></ol></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="5" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Hence, what are the basic standards of in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">formation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">should be made available to councillors to allow them to effectively and meaningfully scrutinise the ongoing performance of the service provider throughout the lifetime of the contract.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="6" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.11pt; padding-left:6.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">How can a councillor assess if the service provider is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> failing to meet the required standards of performance and how can they act to protect council taxpayers.  For example, if they wanted to terminate the contract.  How can they do so if they have no indication as to the break clauses within the agreement or</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> if any exist at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">all?</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Open and fair tendering processe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">s</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As stated above</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> once the initial services contract is awarded to the outsourced company, in this case One Connect Limited, it is likely the organisation will seek </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">provide more services.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A recent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> example of the Lancashire County Council’s Fleet Services Maintenance contract highlights how difficult it can be to maintain a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> open and fair tendering process.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="3" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">BT Fleet Services were asked to carry out a review of the in-house fleet maintenance service</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s at Lancashire County Cou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ncil.  The report was dated </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3 April 2012.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="4" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">At the end of 2012 One Connect Limited submitted a proposal to Lancashire County Council to take over the running of the service.  At this time there was no formal proposal or a competiti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ve tender brief from the County Council advertising the out-sourcing of the service.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="5" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In January 2013 an article was published in the Lancashire Evening </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Post, which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> highlighted the inconsistency of the County Council’s position with regard to their intenti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ons over Fleet Services.  </span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="6" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.11pt; padding-left:6.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">On 8 January Lancashire County Council had written to the trade unions informing them they were considering tendering the service.  However, a county council spokesperson is quoted in the Lancashire Evening Post article </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">saying,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“We’re not currently considering any proposals for changes to this service”. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Evidence of the correspondence with the trade unions would suggest that this was not correct.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="7" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Then on 19 February 2013 the county c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ouncil changed their position yet again.  They</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> issued a formal tender brief.  Within a matter of two weeks the county council had reconsidered their position, they now had plans to tender the fleet maintenance service and had issued a formal tender brief.  This is unbelievable speed for a matter, whic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">h Lancashire County Council had said they were not considering.  Once again this raises issues on the role and function of the accountable officer within the local authority?</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="8" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The deadline for the submissions was 5 April 2013.  A formal decision was to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">taken by the leader of the county council on 26 April 2013.  A £5 million contract was to be signed off merely one week prior to the county council polling day and during purdah.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="9" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.5pt; padding-left:7.5pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Information I have received indicates that only BT and One Connect Limited h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ad an opportunity to review the service ahead of submitting their tender.  Other bidders did not have equal access.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="10" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.5pt; padding-left:7.5pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is clear a potential exists within this One Connect Limited model of outsourcing to become a monopoly given the unrivalled access to inf</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ormation and services.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Fundamental breakdown of accountability, openness and transpare</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">nc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">y in local government</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">All the issues I have outlined above in this memorandum for the Communities and Local Government Committee demonstrate that at the heart of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">outsourcing in the case of One Connect Limited there is a fundamental lack of accountability, openness and transparency.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">When </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">democratically elected</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> representatives are prevented from fulfilling their legal duties and ensuring the council taxpayers intere</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sts are protected this can only serve to weaken local government.  It can only undermine the raison d’etre of local councillors. </span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="3" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Recent events regarding the payments to the former One Connect Limited Chief Executive, which have been widely reported in th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e regional media further demonstrates the lack of openness and transparency in addition to the examples outlined above.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="4" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">On Monday 30 September a report was presented to Lancashire County Council’s Audit and Governance Committee.  The report questions the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">authorisation of payments to the Chief Executive of One Connect Limited.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="5" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In essence, it was understood that the Chief Executive would be paid a salary of £40,000 per annum for 2.5 days per week.  According to a Lancashire County Council report he received</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> payments totalling over £600,000.  It transpired that, without the County Treasurer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s knowledge, two payments were made – one in June 2013 and one in July 2013.  These are just prior to his resignation and employment as the One Connect Limited Chief Execu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tive ceasing on 31</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">st</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> August 2013.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="6" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.11pt; padding-left:6.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This situation has raised questions about who was the employing organisation – was it the local authority, the joint venture or the private sector partner.  Where is the assurance within the system and how do such arrange</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ments get authorised?</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Concluding Remarks</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is my genuine belief that models of outsourcing such as One Connect Limited pose some far-reaching and fundamental questions about how local government functions and the principles on which it governs with the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">will of its residents.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; font-weight:bold; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>